  "response": "No, variance and standard deviation are related, but they are not the same thing.\n\n*   **Variance** is a measure of how spread out a set of numbers is. It is calculated as the average of the squared differences from the mean.\n\n*   **Standard deviation** is the square root of the variance. It is also a measure of how spread out a set of numbers is, but it is expressed in the same units as the original data, which makes it easier to interpret.\n\nIn summary, standard deviation is the square root of variance. They both measure dispersion, but standard deviation is more commonly used because it's in the same units as the original data.",
